45.000000 45.000000 0 0 "Curve 1" }}}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.
  Polynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  There are several features about
 the graphs of polynomials which are important to track.  These featur
es inform us about the behavior of the function.  Those features inclu
de the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of the function                   \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those values \+
where the graph crosses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the
 equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    reg
ions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the
 function are positive" }{TEXT 306 24 " has to do with x values" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in
 particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercep
ts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 " \+
   c.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the v
alues of the function are negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "  \+
                     Those regions where the graph lies below the x-ax
is.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, the
se regions are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infini
ty." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the functi
on" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "                       The value w
here the graph crosses the y-axis.  The value of the function when x =
 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }{TEXT 305 
24 " has to do with y values" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "        \+
               For a polynomial, its values will become either arbitra
rily large in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a negative sens
e as the domain values tend to infinity.  Graphically, the values on t
he graph will growth arbitrarily large positively (go up off the graph
) or arbitrarily large negative (go down off the graph) as the domain \+
values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "           \+
            Similar behavior holds true for approaches to negative inf
inity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
150 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the po
lynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features o
f the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomi
al find each of the above five graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.)
:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 6*x^2+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"
