e infinity right, positive infinity left" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extreme v
alues and monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathered above
 about intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important informat
ion can be determined from the so called \"critical points\" of a poly
nomial.  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercepts of its
 derivative.  Since the derivative of a function at a point represents
 the slope of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at th
e point, then the intercepts of the derivative are places where the th
e tangent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizontal lines. \+
 At such places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  Elsew
here the graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For a polynom
ial, local extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) must occu
r at the intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are imp
ortant in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points
 of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 100 "                    \+
  For a polynomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of the p
olynomial " }{TEXT 309 39 "where the green line crosses the x axis" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 68 "     g.    local maximum points of the gr
aph of a function y = f(x) " }{TEXT 310 46 "substitute where x=0 and p
ut in function (subs" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "                \+
      These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which th
e y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nearby values
 on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (
x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a function
 y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                      Thes
e are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-value \+
is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values on the g
raph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) mus
t be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
109 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function wher
e the values of the function are increasing " }{TEXT 307 25 "slope inc
reasing x values" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                    \+
   Those regions where the graph rises as the graph is traversed from \+
left to right.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polyn
omials, these regions are bounded by the critical points and may stret
ch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 109 "     j.    regi
ons (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the \+
function are decreasing " }{TEXT 308 25 "slope decreasing x values" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph falls as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For \+
a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these region
s are bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity.
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For \+
each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.
  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features of the gra
ph.  Include the graph of the deriviative of the polynomial on the plo
t.   Plot the function in red and the derviative in green.   " }{TEXT 
269 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of the abov
e ten graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = \+
