-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 204 "5.  Three-dimensional plots.  \+
Maple can also provide representations for graphs of functions of two \+
variables.  The graphs of such functions are surfaces in three-dimensi
onal space.  The Maple command is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     " }{TEXT 270 0 "" }{TEXT 271 4 "plot
" }{TEXT 272 2 "3d" }{TEXT -1 2 "( " }{TEXT 273 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 2 "
, " }{TEXT 274 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 8 "=range, " }{TEXT 275 0 "" }{TEXT 
276 2 "y=" }{TEXT -1 19 "range [, options]);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "where " }{TEXT 277 4 "expr" }
{TEXT 281 1 " " }{TEXT -1 24 "is a symbolic expression" }{TEXT 279 1 "
 " }{TEXT -1 48 "which represents the function to be plotted and " }
{TEXT 278 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 282 0 "" }{TEXT 283 1 "y" }
{TEXT 284 0 "" }{TEXT -1 44 " are the two independent variables used i
n  " }{TEXT 280 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 25 "  to define the function." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }
{TEXT 285 0 "" }{TEXT 286 6 "plot3d" }{TEXT 287 0 "" }{TEXT -1 238 " c
ommand will generate a surface plot for the function over the rectangu
lar range specfied in the command statement.  The surface plot can be \+
rotated, tipped over and turned around to see the surface plot from al
l side and all viewpoints." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 278 "For each of the following functions provide a pl
ot which shows the graph.  Choose reasonable values for the ranges of \+
x and y.  Rotate, where appropriate, to present a good view of the gra
ph.  The last two graphs are implicitly defined functions which requir
e the Maple command " }{TEXT 297 0 "" }{TEXT 298 15 "implicitplot3d " 
}{TEXT 299 0 "" }{TEXT -1 29 "which is part of the package " }{TEXT 
300 0 "" }{TEXT 301 5 "plots" }{TEXT 302 0 "" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }
